### 1. Brief Summary of the Facts  
The case involves **So Ping Chi**, former General Manager and Principal Surveyor of Ships at the Marine Department of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Government. From **April 2007 to October 2012**, he issued and maintained a **non-enforcement instruction** directing subordinate ship inspectors not to enforce the requirement under *Merchant Shipping (Local Vessels) (Safety and Survey) Regulation* (Cap 548G) that **children’s lifejackets** be provided on vessels licensed *before* 2 January 2007 (so-called "old vessels"). The regulation mandated 100% adult lifejackets plus 5% children’s lifejackets for all vessels operating in Hong Kong waters, with a 12-month grace period until 1 January 2008. So Ping Chi’s instruction, inherited from his predecessor, exempted "old vessels" from this requirement, effectively allowing them to comply with the *old law* (which required lifejackets for only 40% of passengers, with no children’s lifejackets). The instruction remained in place for **over five years**, until the **Lamma Island ferry collision in October 2012**, which prompted a Commission of Inquiry that uncovered the non-enforcement policy. So Ping Chi was **convicted of misconduct in public office** (a common law offense punishable under section 101I(1) of the Criminal Procedure Ordinance) and sentenced to **16 months’ imprisonment**. He appealed both conviction and sentence. The Court of Appeal **upheld the conviction** but **reduced the sentence** to time already served (4.5 months), citing the lack of criminal prosecution against his predecessors and successors who similarly implemented the policy.

